  "summary": "Hercule Poirot continues his unofficial investigation by interviewing several individuals at the hotel. He first visits Kenneth Marshall, who is busy typing. When Poirot asks if Marshall showered after typing but before playing tennis on the day of his wife's murder, Marshall denies it, stating he only showered an hour prior to playing tennis.\n\nPoirot then meets Mr. Gardner at the bar. Mr. Gardner expresses his suspicion that the police are withholding information from the family and mentions his desire to take his sensitive wife away from the hotel. When Poirot asks for his opinion on the late Elena Marshall, Mr. Gardner dismisses her as a \"complete fool.\"\n\nOn the sun terrace, Rosamund Darnley approaches Poirot and acknowledges his investigation. She suggests that Elena Marshall may have been murdered by a vain and sensitive man from her past who might have followed her to the island and used the foggy weather to arrive at Fairy Bay undetected. Poirot counters this theory, arguing that a murderer would likely not risk being seen crossing the hotel in daylight. Poirot then questions Rosamund about whether she took a bath that morning, noting that no one else seems to have used a bath. He also observes that Rosamund wears Jaeger No. 8 perfume, the same brand used by Mrs. Marshall. Poirot concludes the conversation by asking Rosamund if she visited the fairy cave on the morning of the incident.",
  "summary_whitespace_tokens": 235,
